Input.threadtitle: complicated way to explain simultaneous equations
Input.posts:
Im sorry bbut if you have M rows of data like in the housibg examle and lets say 4 'features' isnt this all about solving for 5 variables (x0, x1, x2, x3, x4) using the M constraint equations as an over determined system of equations? This is the same as the secondary school work of simultaneous equations: x + y = 2 x - y = 0 sort of thing... just that here were have 5 and not 2 unknowns! This would also make it easy to talk about minimum number of 'data points' in order to match number of constraints to degree of freedom *n+1' etc!! I found the Normal equation lecture avoiding this basic math aspect that we have learnt in school!! and making it more 'pro coder who does not care about algebra'
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi, It's only possible to solve such system when there is no approximation or noise in data. In that case, we don't need machine learning since we can pin down mathematically every parameters of our system. In any other cases, if we try to solve such over-determined system, we will end up with equations like $$x = 2.2 * y + 2$$, $$x = 2.3 * y + 1.9$$, $$x = 2.4 * y + 2.1$$ for every variables, meaning the system do not have any exact solution. That is why normal equation and linear regression are not solving the system directly but minimize a cost function which is a representation of the error from predictions to ground truth.

Input.threadtitle: global optimum and local optimum
Input.posts:
what's the main difference between the local and global optimum and how is the solution is considered when we only reach a local optimum? is the global minimum the best solution
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Ahmed, the difference is that global optimum is the best choice in our complete space and local optimum is the best choice in one area of our complete space. In other words, there are only 1 global optimum and several (if any) local optimums. The problem is that we don't know if our algorithm is found global or local optimum ,so we have to perform several calculations with different initial vectors in order to be sure that we found global optimum. For example, we run 10 calculations and the best result (minimum of all 10 results) is our global optimum. Of course, we can't be 100% sure we found global optimum, but at least we have better probability that we found it. With 100 different calculations we will have even better probability to find global optimum. During this course you don't need to consider if you find global optimum or not because all inputs are already correctly set in order to find global optimum.

Input.threadtitle: Learning rate thoughts
Input.posts:
Why do we have a constant learning rate? As per the lecture notes, the convergence becomes slower and slower towards the end as the slope becomes less and less. Can we not start increasing the learning rate when the slope is getting closer to zero? Just to test this idea, in the gradientDescentMulti, I added a 'alpha = alpha * 1.025;' for each iteration and the convergence was very fast. Obviously there must be some problem with this as I am sure I am not the first person to come up with this seemingly great idea :)
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
If you choose a bigger learning rate you may learn fast but you increase the chances that you will overshoot. The point is to come up with a very good model, not just adequate, so you need to get as close to the bottom of the gradient descent as possible. How you gonna do that if you have a big learning rate, except by pure luck?
Instructor's post : If you choose a bigger learning rate you may learn fast but you increase the chances that you will overshoot. The point is to come up with a very good model, not just adequate, so you need to get as close to the bottom of the gradient descent as possible. How you gonna do that if you have a big learning rate, except by pure luck?
Upvotes:
3

Title: Linking forum posts -ml-005-10-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Multiple Features Video Quiz - '[Math Processing Error]'
Input.posts:
The quiz question in Multiple Features video. It seems basic but I don't want to ignore it. What is the [Math Processing Error] in this question? What knowledge/information we are supposed to use to get the correct answer? I hope someone can help.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
The pages on the discussion forums make heavy use of Ajax to prevent the clients from fetching whole pages over and over. The math is also represented using Mathjax, and what can happen is that one part of the page gets refreshed properly but another part does not, since the page is not loaded from scratch. Usually a hard page refresh (forcing the page to reload) with Ctrl+F5 or the equivalent on your OS will correct the situation.
